Text.Value: I've never been in a broadsheet before - where can I buy a copy?
Why, the Baldur's Mouth Gazette, of course! I would certainly recommend picking up a copy in the near future.
No one ever does, my sweet. But look on the bright side, you'll be famous.
Well, it's about damn time! Which of my many deeds did you chronicle?
No, dear reader, I'm afraid one of my columns is not in the latest issue. 'Print issues limiting space', according to our esteemed editor.

EditorData.NodeContext: said with pure, unadulterated disdain towards the editor who's cut her column

Text.Value: Oh, come now - everyone loves a good obituary. And the one in our latest edition is to die for.
Well, then there's a high chance that your testimony has already found its way into the latest edition!
I work for the greatest broadsheet in this storied city. It's my job to know who is who. I imagine you'll be becoming quite familiar with it soon.
Are your readers not also people of Baldur's Gate?
Leave.
Oh, you again. If you want a broadsheet, I'd advise acquiring one sharpish. We're running low. Printer issues, says Ettvard.

EditorData.NodeContext: said with pure, unadulterated disdain towards the editor who's cut her column

Text.Value: I'm afraid your piece hasn't gone to print yet, my sweet. Patience.
Oh ho. You. I know you. How delightful to meet in person, though you're shorter than I expected.
Well, if I just told you, you'd have no reason to read our latest edition!
You must have mistaken me for someone. I'm Bhaal's favourite child.
Look, sorry, I'm looking for new interview subjects - we need some fresh takes on the demise of the dearly departed Duke Gortash.
Go on then - what really happened?
I never asked to be written about.
Now, if you'll excuse me, I've really said rather to much and written rather too little. Good day.
You are, after all, the star of the next Baldur's Mouth Gazette.
Sorry, how do you know me?
And what's the headline of that edition...?
My name's Estra Stir. Journalist. I speak to the people of Baldur's Gate so our readers don't have to.
Toodle-oo! I look forward to seeing you grace our front pages.
Well, there's people, and then there's people. You, my dear, are people.
I bet you do.
It's just an opinion. It's my job to have them - I meant no offence.
You are quite correct - the best broadsheet around. I would certainly recommend picking up a copy in the near future.
It's our juiciest edition in an age - bound to get everyone talking about you.
I look forward to reading it.
If I told you, you'd lose the fun of reading it yourself.
It's a real shame your illustrious stint on the broadsheet covers was upstaged - Lord Gortash's death would do that though, I suppose.
You work for the Baldur's Mouth Gazette, I presume.
You're already set to feature in the Baldur's Mouth Gazette, dear. Let me find some other subjects.
What broadsheet do you work for, Estra?
Leave.
'How' is such an overrated question. It's the who and the why that matter, darling.
Rude.
With grandiose delusions like that, you'll fit perfectly in the news business. Pleasure to meet you - and as for me...
I can tell an inquisitive sort when I see one - want the real story behind the untimely demise of Lord Enver Gortash?
Your write-up in the latest Gazette might seem harsh, but think about it - so few people ever experience true infamy. It's a privilege, in a way.
Leave.
Pick up the Baldur's Mouth - our city's broadsheet of record - to find out more. Dear reader, you will be most satisfied.
Well well - the very unlikely hero of our latest gazette. Don't let the fame go to your head, now.
Darling, we can't let the readers decide what the content is. We've editors for that.
Seems your stint in the harsh light of infamy was to be short-lived, my sweet. Not as short lived as Lord Gortash, mind you.
Don't I get a say in this?
It's not out yet, but any of the Gazetteers can sell you a copy when it's printed.
Can you believe the injustice? Our beloved editor falls in the line of duty, and they don't give me his job? Disgusting.
In fact, you're the star of the next edition.
You have me at a disadvantage, I've no idea who you are.
I'd rather never hear that prick's name again, thanks.
No need - I was there.
Nice to meet you - I really must get going.
I read your write-up in the latest edition - my condolences. Ettvard really went for the unmentionables.
How did you know who I was?

Synopsis: Estra Stir is a gossip columnist for the Baldurs Mouth. She has a devilish artifact, the Eye ofTitivilus,  that allows her to detect the thoghts of the people she is talking too. She wants to pump the players for juicy personal details to print in her gossip column.
